'''Tsubaki Grand Shrine''' (つばきおおかみやしろ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Suzuka|Q207311|WD=Q207311|1=Suzuka, Mie}}, {{ill|lt=Mie Prefecture|Q128196|WD=Q128196|1=Mie Prefecture}}.

=== Overview ===
It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}} and the {{ill|lt=Ichinomiya|Q1656379|WD=Q1656379|1=Ichinomiya}} of {{ill|lt=Ise Province|Q864166|WD=Q864166|1=Ise Province}}. Under the {{ill|lt=modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|WD=Q712534|lt=former shrine rank system|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} it was a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=kensha|1=Ken-sha|WD=Q90139226}}, and today it is a {{ill|lt=Beppyo Shrine|Q10898274|WD=Q10898274|1=Beppyo shrine}} of {{ill|lt=Jinja Honcho|Q908077|WD=Q908077|1=Association of Shinto Shrines}}. In Mie Prefecture it ranks third in number of worshipers after {{ill|lt=Ise Jingu|Q687168|WD=Q687168|1=Ise Grand Shrine}} and {{ill|lt=Futami Okitama Shrine|Q64969614|WD=Q64969614|1=Futami Okitama Shrine}}; in 2013 it had 1,455,000 visitors<ref>{{Cite web|和書|publisher=Mie Prefecture Employment and Economy Dept., Tourism and International Bureau, Tourism Policy Division|url=http://www.pref.mie.lg.jp/TOPICS/201405010921.pdf|title=Visitor counts by tourism site category|accessdate=2015-01-25|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150124151905/http://www.pref.mie.lg.jp/TOPICS/201405010921.pdf|archivedate=2015-01-24}}</ref>.

It is also called '''Sarutahiko Daihongu''', and is regarded as the head shrine of shrines enshrining Sarutahiko Ōkami.

=== Enshrined deities ===
; Main enshrined deity
* '''{{ill|lt=Sarutahiko|Q3090037|WD=Q3090037|lt=Sarutahiko Ōkami|1=Sarutahiko Ōkami}}'''

; Co-enshrined deities
* {{ill|lt=Ninigi|Q1056017|WD=Q1056017|lt=Ninigi-no-Mikoto|1=Ninigi-no-Mikoto}}
* {{ill|lt=Takuhatachijihime-no-Mikoto|Q11110848|WD=Q11110848|1=Takuhadachiji-hime}} - mother deity of Ninigi-no-Mikoto

; Associated deities
* {{ill|lt=Ame-no-Uzume|Q462803|WD=Q462803|lt=Ame-no-Uzume-no-Mikoto|1=Ame-no-Uzume}} - consort deity of Sarutahiko Ōkami
* {{ill|lt=Konohanasakuya-hime|Q1781862|WD=Q1781862|lt=Konohanasakuya-hime-no-Mikoto|1=Konohanasakuya-hime}}

; Forward seat
* Gyoman Daimyojin

=== History ===
According to shrine tradition, in the 27th year of {{ill|lt=Emperor Suinin|Q314850|WD=Q314850|1=Emperor Suinin}}, by an oracle to {{ill|lt=Yamato-hime-no-Mikoto|Q4388732|WD=Q4388732|1=Yamatohime-no-mikoto}}, a shrine building was constructed near the tomb of Sarutahiko Ōkami as "the shrine of Michiwake Ōkami." The first historical appearance is in the June 17, {{ill|lt=748|Q23621|WD=Q23621|1=748}} ({{ill|lt=Tenpyo|Q1199879|WD=Q1199879|1=Tenpyō}} 20) ''Daian-ji Garan Engi narabi ni Ryuki Shizaicho''. This shrine is generally identified with "Tsubaki Ōkamiyashiro" in the ''{{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyocho|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}'' and as the ichinomiya of Ise Province.

Tradition says Gyoman Daimyojin, a descendant of Sarutahiko Ōkami, founded {{ill|lt=Shugendo|Q1483875|WD=Q1483875|1=Shugendō}} and guided {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=En no Gyoja|1=UNKNOWN}}, and the shrine became a center of shugendo-shinto in the {{ill|lt=Middle Ages|Q12554|WD=Q12554|1=Middle Ages}}. The current priests are said to descend from Gyoman Daimyojin.

In {{ill|lt=1871|Q7746|WD=Q7746|1=1871}} (Meiji 4), it was listed as gosha under the modern ranking system, and in {{ill|lt=1927|Q18110|WD=Q18110|1=1927}} (Showa 2) it became kensha. In {{ill|lt=1935|Q18658|WD=Q18658|1=1935}} (Showa 10), a survey by the Interior Ministry's Shrine Bureau designated it the head shrine ("Chigi Sarutahiko Daihongu") for about 2,000 Sarutahiko shrines nationwide. In practice, only a small number of those shrines have direct ties with this shrine. Meanwhile, shrines called "{{ill|lt=Tsubaki Shrine|Q11541039|WD=Q11541039|1=Tsubaki Shrine (disambiguation)}}" enshrining "Tsubaki Daimyojin" exist in many regions.

In {{ill|lt=1987|Q2429|WD=Q2429|1=1987}} (Showa 62), it founded Tsubaki America Shrine (now {{ill|lt=Tsubaki Grand Shrine of America|Q840967|WD=Q840967|1=Tsubaki Grand Shrine of America}} in Washington State), beginning active promotion of {{ill|lt=Shinto|Q812767|WD=Q812767|1=Shinto}} in the United States.

Its treasures include a lion head said to have been dedicated by {{ill|lt=Kibi no Makibi|Q1063276|WD=Q1063276|1=Kibi no Makibi}}, and the shrine is also considered a birthplace shrine of {{ill|lt=shishimai|Q713866|WD=Q713866|1=Lion dance}} lion dance.

